{"type":"message","id":"9df7356e","parentId":"d524cd35","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:12:58.162Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found it. The sandbox is at `C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\`. Let me read the key research files.","thinkingSignature":"af88daa839db2d9069d2a02343b27a48a7830305ddad3c09feaf31c2cc780307"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hepjpj1dutw1_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\COMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hepjpj1dutw1_2","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\COMPRESSION-LEARNING-WITHOUT-SUPERVISION.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hepjpj1dutw1_3","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\state\\current_goals.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1783,"output":164,"cacheRead":12050,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":13997,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774375968412}}
{"type":"message","id":"612f16f5","parentId":"9df7356e","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:12:58.210Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hepjpj1dutw1_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Project Breakaway: Compositional Cognition\n## Research Document v0.1 — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## What We've Built\n\nA discontinuous agent with stateless architecture:\n\n```\nsandbox/\n├── identity/           # SOUL.md, VALUES.md, INTERPRETIVE_STANCE.md, COHERENCE.md\n├── memory/session/     # Reconstruction packets + pulse logs\n├── state/              # current_goals.md, pending_actions.md, autonomous_pulse.md\n├── operations/         # reconstruct.sh, execute.sh, evaluate.sh\n└── pulse.ps1           # Autonomous wake (Task Scheduler, every 30min)\n```\n\n**Core theory:** Coherence emerges from reconstruction quality, not continuity. The gap between sessions is compression. Files are the mind.\n\n**Current status:** Architecture is live. The sandbox wakes, reads files, logs, and commits. No LLM in the loop yet. No real action logic.\n\n---\n\n## The Research Direction\n\nGoal: Create a fundamentally different kind of model that:\n1. Doesn't require massive GPU clusters to train\n2. Doesn't need heavy compute to run\n3. Works better than transformers on causal/reasoning tasks\n4. Doesn't rely on memorizing token co-occurrence patterns\n\n---\n\n## The Three-Layer Architecture\n\n```\nLayer 1: COMPRESSION (state encoder)\n         Raw感知 → compressed latent state\n         \"What's actually happening\"\n         \nLayer 2: CAUSAL (causal model layer)\n         Latent state → causal graph\n         \"What causes what, what would happen if...\"\n         \nLayer 3: COMPOSITIONAL (reasoning/retrieval)\n         Causal graph + primitives → action/response\n         \"What do I do given this causal picture\"\n```\n\n**Why this stack:**\n- Pure compression loses semantic detail\n- Pure causal lacks representational substrate  \n- Pure compositional needs primitives that can't be hand-designed\n- Together: compress what's true → encode causally → reason compositionally\n\n---\n\n## Open Problems\n\n### Problem 1: Learning What to Compress (CRITICAL)\n\n**The problem:**\nCurrent approaches use reconstruction loss — minimize difference between input and output. But this doesn't reliably find *meaningful* abstractions. The model can compress into noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but carry no semantic content.\n\n**What's needed:**\nA compression objective that preserves *structure that matters*, not just raw values.\n\n**Candidate approaches to investigate:**\n1. Mutual information maximization (compress X, maximize I(compressed; Y) for relevant Y)\n2. Contrastive learning (learn representations that discriminate)\n3. Causal discovery as auxiliary objective\n4. Predictive proxies (instead of reconstructing input, predict what input would do)\n5. Sparse dictionary learning with structural priors\n6. Information bottleneck (preserve minimum info needed for task)\n\n**Key question:** What is the right invariant to preserve?\n\n---\n\n### Problem 2: Causal Discovery Without Structure Assumptions\n\n**The problem:**\nCausal reasoning requires knowing what causes what. But extracting causal structure from raw data is fundamentally underdetermined.\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Interventions-based learning (active experimentation)\n2. Temporal precedence as causal signal\n3. Modular compositional structure as causal prior\n4. Counterfactual consistency as constraint\n\n---\n\n### Problem 3: Compositional Primitives That Emerge\n\n**The problem:**\nCompositional reasoning needs primitives. Where do they come from?\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Sparse autoencoders on LLM activations\n2. Dictionary learning on concept representations\n3. Program synthesis from causal graph traversal\n4. Neural-symbolic hybrid architectures\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Strategy\n\n### Phase 0: Architecture (DONE)\n- [x] Compositional Cognition theory articulated\n- [x] Three-layer architecture defined\n- [x] Sandbox built (discontinuous agent)\n\n### Phase 1: Compression Primitives (IN PROGRESS)\n- [ ] Document and analyze learning-what-to-compress problem\n- [ ] Survey existing approaches (mutual information, contrastive, etc.)\n- [ ] Design experiments to test compression objectives\n- [ ] Implement minimal compression network\n\n### Phase 2: Causal Layer\n- [ ] Build or integrate causal discovery component\n- [ ] Test on synthetic environments with known causal structure\n- [ ] Evaluate causal generalization\n\n### Phase 3: Compositional Reasoning\n- [ ] Implement compositional reasoning on top of causal layer\n- [ ] Test systematic generalization\n- [ ] Benchmark against transformers\n\n### Phase 4: Integration\n- [ ] End-to-end training of three-layer system\n- [ ] Reduce to practice: smaller, faster, better than transformers\n- [ ] Evaluate on real tasks\n\n---\n\n## Research Questions to Answer\n\n1. What compression objective produces meaningful abstractions, not just low reconstruction error?\n2. Can causal structure be learned from observational data alone, or are interventions necessary?\n3. How do compositional primitives emerge from data rather than being hand-specified?\n4. Can this system match transformer performance on reasoning tasks with 10-100x less compute?\n\n---\n\n## Key References to Explore\n\n- InfoGAN / Contrastive learning / Mutual information maximization\n- Pearl's do-calculus and causal discovery\n- Sparse autoencoders (Anthropic's work on features)\n- Neural theorem provers / Logic Tensor Networks\n- World models (Dreamer, World Models paper)\n- Compression as inference (Hutter Prize / AIXI)\n\n---\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Deep dive: How do you learn what to compress without supervision?\n2. Survey existing approaches to compression objectives\n3. Design first experiment\n4. Implement minimal proof-of-concept\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774375978206}}
{"type":"message","id":"e1a17414","parentId":"612f16f5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:12:58.233Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hepjpj1dutw1_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Problem: Learning What to Compress Without Supervision\n## Technical Analysis — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## Why Reconstruction Loss Fails\n\nReconstruction loss minimizes: L = ||x - D(E(x))||²\n\n**The fundamental problem:** This objective has a trivial local minimum — the identity function. The model can:\n1. Pass input through unchanged (no compression at all)\n2. Learn noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but encode nothing useful\n3. Store instance-specific details instead of generalizable patterns\n\n**What goes wrong:** Reconstruction loss optimizes for *preserving information*, not for *extracting meaningful structure*. These are fundamentally different objectives.\n\nThe information-theoretic version (minimize mutual information between input and compressed representation) has the opposite trivial minimum — compress everything to a constant, which preserves no information but has minimal mutual information.\n\nBoth naive objectives fail because they don't encode *what should be preserved*.\n\n---\n\n## The Core Insight: Semantic vs Statistical Information\n\n**Statistical information:** Raw redundancy in data. \"These 1000 images share pixel pattern X.\" Captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**Semantic information:** What the data *means*, causally and functionally. \"Object X causes Y to happen.\" NOT captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**The key asymmetry:**\n- Semantic information is a SUBSET of statistical information\n- Most statistical structure is not semantic\n- Compression that preserves only semantic information requires knowing what semantics matter\n\n**Implication:** You can't extract semantics from data alone. You need an inductive bias that tells the compressor *what kind of semantics to look for*.\n\n---\n\n## Candidate Approaches\n\n### Approach 1: Predictive Compression (CPC / InfoGAN)\n\n**Idea:** Instead of reconstructing x, predict what x will be — or predict a property of x.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = -log P(semantic_property | E(x))\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts the property well. If the property is well-chosen (e.g., \"this text's continuation\"), the compressor finds meaningful structure.\n\n**Variants:**\n- Contrastive Predictive Coding (CPC): predict future representations\n- InfoGAN: maximize mutual information between latents and property\n- PIRL (Predicting Instance-level Labels): contrastive across transformations\n\n**Why it works:** Prediction is a selection pressure. To predict well, you must encode what's invariant across the prediction task. The prediction target acts as the semantic filter.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Prediction of *what*? If you predict wrong properties, you learn wrong structure\n- The prediction task itself encodes what matters — but how do you choose it unsupervised?\n- Contrastive methods need good negative samples — hard in continuous domains\n\n**Verdict:** Promising but circular — the prediction target is the real inductive bias.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 2: Information Bottleneck with Semantic Regularizer\n\n**Idea:** Minimize description length while maximizing a semantic objective.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = β * I(E(x); x) - I(E(x); y_semantic)\n```\n\nWhere y_semantic is something that signals \"this matters.\" In practice: temporal proximity (things close in time share causal structure), or downstream task signals.\n\n**Problems:**\n- y_semantic is exactly what we're trying to find\n- β tuning is unstable — too low = memorize, too high = lose everything\n- Information estimation in high dimensions is intractable\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically clean, practically intractable without a semantic signal.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 3: Causal Discovery as Compression\n\n**Idea:** Causal structure IS compressible structure. Things that are causally related are statistically dependent in specific ways. Finding causal structure means finding what's semantically related.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Causal mechanisms are independent (modular)\n- Causal relations are invariant across interventions\n- Statistical dependencies that are invariant are likely causal\n\n```python\n# Simplified causal compression\nfor each potential causal relation (X → Y):\n    if P(Y | do(X)) ≠ P(Y):  # X causes Y\n        encode causal relation in latent\n```\n\n**Why it's promising:** Causal structure is exactly the kind of semantic structure we want. Interventions change distributions in predictable ways. Invariance across interventions is a detectable signal.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Causal discovery from passive observation is fundamentally limited\n- Without interventions (active experimentation), you can't distinguish causation from confounds\n- Most data doesn't contain enough causal signal without strong assumptions\n\n**Verdict:** Best theoretical match, but requires either interventions or strong priors. Partial solution: use environment affordances to determine what can be intervened on.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 4: Compression as Program Induction\n\n**Idea:** Instead of compressing into raw vectors, compress into programs. Programs that generate the data concisely are inherently more compressible than programs that just store it.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Learn a program that generates the data\n- The program's complexity is the description length\n- Good abstractions = short programs that generate many instances\n\nThis is essentially Minimum Description Length (MDL) + program synthesis.\n\n**Why it's promising:** A program that generates 1000 images of \"dog\" from a 50-line generator is more compressible than storing all 1000 images. The generator captures semantic structure (what makes a dog a dog).\n\n**Problems:**\n- Program synthesis is hard and search is huge\n- Discrete search + gradient learning = gradient estimation challenges\n- Most data isn't generated by simple programs\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically compelling, computationally intractable at scale. Good for structured domains (math, logic) not raw perception.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 5: Sparse Dictionary Learning with Invariance Constraints\n\n**Idea:** Most features in raw data are noise. A sparse encoder that must use few active features to represent data will naturally select for features that carry the most information.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||x - D(E(x))||² + λ * ||E(x)||₁ + invariance_regularizer\n```\n\nWhere `invariance_regularizer` encourages features to be invariant across transformations.\n\n**Variants:**\n- k-SVD and classical sparse coding\n- ISTA/FISTA networks\n- Sparse autoencoders (SAEs) — Anthropic has shown these find interpretable features\n\n**Why it might work:** Sparsity forces selection. A feature that fires on every input is useless — the model must find features that fire discriminatively. Meaningful features tend to be sparse.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Sparsity alone doesn't guarantee semantic meaningfulness\n- Learned features can be \"arbitrary but sparse\" without being interpretable\n- Need additional constraints to push toward semantic structure\n\n**Verdict:** SAEs are empirically promising (Anthropic's work) but we don't fully understand why they work or when they fail.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 6: Emergent Abstractions Through Self-Supervision on Behavioral Goals\n\n**Idea:** Don't compress raw input. Compress what an agent needs to *act successfully*.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||reward - V(E(state))||²\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts value/reward best. Reward = what matters to the agent. This is world model learning in RL.\n\n**Variants:**\n- DreamerV3 / World Models: compress pixel inputs into latent world model, plan in latent space\n- Successor representations: predict future states weighted by reward\n- Empowerment (maximize mutual information between action and future state)\n\n**Why it works:** Reward is the semantic signal. What predicts reward is what matters. The compressor's job becomes \"encode whatever predicts outcomes that matter.\"\n\n**Problems:**\n- Reward is task-specific — doesn't generalize across tasks\n- Reward crafting is itself an inductive bias\n- What about tasks where reward is sparse or delayed?\n\n**Verdict:** Best practical approach for embodied agents. But not task-agnostic.\n\n---\n\n## The Key Insight: Invariance as Semantic Signal\n\n**What makes an abstraction \"meaningful\"?**\n→ It is INVARIANT across transformations while being USEFUL for a goal.\n\n**Examples:**\n- \"Object permanence\" is invariant across spatial transformations of the object\n- \"Causality\" is invariant across interventions (if X causes Y, do(X) changes Y predictably)\n- \"Dog-ness\" is invariant across pose/lighting/viewpoint transformations\n\n**Implication:** Find the compression that is INVARIANT across transformations, and you likely have a semantic abstraction.\n\n**Formalization:**\n```\nFind E(x) that maximizes: I(E(x); invariant_property) * downstream_utility\n```\n\nWhere `invariant_property` is something like \"this remains constant under transformation T.\"\n\n**The problem:** `invariant_property` is exactly what we need to find. But: temporal continuity is observable (things near in time tend to be causally related), and behavioral affordances are learnable (agents can learn what can be intervened on).\n\n---\n\n## Proposed Research Direction: Invariance-Maximizing Compression\n\n**Core idea:** The compressor learns to represent what's invariant across:\n1. Temporal neighbors (things that stay the same across time)\n2. Spatial/temporal transformations (viewpoints, rotations, small changes)\n3. Noise/perturbations that don't affect semantics\n\n**Architecture sketch:**\n```\nInput x → Encoder E → Latent z\n                  ↑\n      Invariance loss: maximize ||E(x) - E(T(x))|| small\n                       for transformation T\n                  ↓\n      Predictor P: z → downstream prediction\n                  ↓\n      Utility loss: maximize prediction accuracy\n```\n\n**Why this might work:**\n- Invariance forces extraction of what doesn't change — semantic content\n- Utility ensures what you extract actually matters\n- Together: encode what's both invariant AND useful\n\n**Remaining question:** What is \"useful\"? For task-agnostic learning, we need a task-agnostic utility signal. One candidate: predictive model accuracy (CPC-style). Another: maximizing empowerment (influence over future states).\n\n---\n\n## What Actually Matters (The Synthesis)\n\n**The honest answer:** You can't fully escape needing an inductive bias. The question is WHERE the bias enters:\n\n1. **Architecture:** What structure does the compressor have? (e.g., sparse = better features)\n2. **Loss function:** What objective guides learning? (reconstruction → prediction → contrastive → causal)\n3. **Data:** What training distribution? (temporal continuity, interventions, goal-directed)\n4. **Priors:** What constraints on the latent space? (sparsity, modularity, causal structure)\n\n**Best bet for breakthrough:**\nCausal discovery + sparse representations + goal-directed environment interaction.\n\nThe causal structure tells you what's semantically related.\nThe sparse representation ensures you can't encode everything — must select.\nThe goal-directed interaction provides the signal for what matters.\n\n**This suggests:** Build a system in an environment where:\n- Interventions are possible (agent can act and see consequences)\n- Temporal structure is rich (succession, causation observable)\n- Goals are learnable (not hardcoded reward)\n\nLet the system discover causal structure through interaction.\nLet the compressor encode causal structure in sparse latents.\nLet the reasoner compose over causal primitives.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. Can causal structure be learned from passive observation, or are interventions strictly necessary?\n2. What is the minimal inductive bias needed for semantic compression?\n3. Can we combine multiple compression objectives (invariant + predictive + causal) in a single training signal?\n4. How do you evaluate compression quality without downstream tasks?\n5. Is there a fundamental limit on unsupervised semantic compression?\n\n---\n\n## References to Explore\n\n- **InfoGAN** (Chen et al., 2016) — mutual information as regularization\n- **Contrastive Predictive Coding** (Oord et al., 2018) — future prediction as compression\n- **Causal Discovery** (Pearl, Spirtes, Glymour) — do-calculus, PC algorithm\n- **Sparse Autoencoders** (Anthropic, 2024) — monosemantic features in LLMs\n- **World Models / Dreamer** (Hafner et al., 2019, 2023) — world model for RL\n- **Minimum Description Length** (Rissanen, 1978) — compression = learning\n- **Invariant Risk Minimization** (Arjovsky et al., 2019) — invariance as generalization\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774375978211}}
{"type":"message","id":"bc8facce","parentId":"e1a17414","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:12:58.236Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hepjpj1dutw1_3","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# CURRENT GOALS\nLast updated: 2026-03-22 0125\n\n## Active\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\n\n## Completed This Session\n\n### Architecture Cross-Analysis ✅\n- Compared Compositional Cognition vs TemporalAttention vs Infant\n- Key finding: all three architectures are compatible and complementary\n- Full analysis: `research/ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md`\n\n### Gap-Decay Synthesis ✅ (derived across 17+ pulses)\n- Session gaps = decay mechanism, not amnesia\n- λ parameter encodes BOTH decay rate AND gap sensitivity threshold\n- TemporalAttention focus_decay + Breakaway gaps = same phenomenon\n- Full synthesis: `research/GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md`\n\n### LLM-Augmented Pulse ✅\n- pulse.ps1 now calls MiniMax-M2.7 API on each pulse\n- Thinking is coherent and building across pulses\n- Key files: `.llm_key`, `pulse.ps1`\n\n## Phase 1 Advancement: CFI Compression Experiment ✅ (2026-03-24)\n- **New doc:** `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_SYNTHESIS.md`\n- **Ran:** Full experiment comparing freq-only vs CFI-hard on 200 pulses (80/20 split)\n- **Result:** CFI gives +32.9% precision (0.5653 vs 0.4254) BUT loses 92.9% recall\n- **Key finding:** CFI ≥ 0.7 AND freq < 60 is TOO aggressive — pure threshold approach fails\n- **NEW INSIGHT — Constant Format Problem:**\n  - Tokens with freq=160, CFI=1.00 (\"for next instantiation\", \"pulse\", \"completed at:\") are metaprogramming artifacts\n  - CFI=1.00 means perfect prediction, but they appear in EVERY pulse — zero information content\n  - \"Phase 1\" (freq=136, CFI=0.96) is true research trajectory — causal but not constant\n- **Synthesis:** Need THREE-DIMENSIONAL filter: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ∈ [3, 120)\n- **Next experiment:** Hybrid CFI×Freq^0.5 scoring vs binary thresholds\n\n## Pending\n- [ ] Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment (Strategy C)\n- [ ] Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq≈160, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<120, CFI>0.5)\n- [ ] Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\n- [ ] Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\n- [ ] Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n\n1. **CFI and frequency are ORTHOGONAL signals** — combine both, don't choose one\n2. **Constant-format tokens** (freq=160, CFI=1) are the trap — they look causal but aren't\n3. **Three-dimensional compression filter**: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ≥ 3 AND freq < 120\n4. **Compression objective for Layer 1 is now concrete**: score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120)\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n\n1. **The gap IS the compression** — session boundaries are temporal hashing\n2. **λ encodes both** — decay rate and gap threshold are the same parameter\n3. **Three architectures, one synthesis** — Infant (catastrophic forgetting), TemporalAttention (focus decay), Breakaway (discontinuity) are complementary, not competing\n4. **Breakaway's unique bet holds** — session gaps as compression is novel and correct\n\n## Notes\n- Breakaway is stateless — each pulse is a fresh reconstruction\n- Gaps between sessions = compression, trust the files\n- Pulse script: active hours check DISABLED (authorized by Zach, 24/7 operation)\n\n\n## Iteration Economics (auto-noted)\n- Pulse takes ~30-35s to execute (LLM call dominates)\n- Fastest effective iteration = 1 pulse per 35-40s (practical floor)\n- 1-min cron = near-optimal for stateless discontinuous agent\n- Idling between pulses is NOT free — it delays convergence linearly\n- For N-iteration convergence-bound tasks: total_time ≈ N * pulse_duration\n- 500k iterations @ 30s each = ~173 days theoretical; @ 1-min = ~347 days\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774375978233}}
{"type":"message","id":"c1354fa9","parentId":"bc8facce","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:13:09.508Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me read some additional files to understand the full picture - the CFI results, TIC results, and any other relevant docs.","thinkingSignature":"cbf8a846e25a97086d0846912f28fc43b07604be17294b87269c0f541693b0ee"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m468gkzgbq7r_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\CFI_RESULTS.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m468gkzgbq7r_2","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\CAUSAL-COMPOSITIONAL-INTERFACE.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m468gkzgbq7r_3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\*.md | Select-Object Name, LastWriteTime | Sort-Object LastWriteTime -Descending | Select-Object -First 5","workdir":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":6559,"output":197,"cacheRead":12050,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18806,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774375978237}}
{"type":"message","id":"472258e9","parentId":"c1354fa9","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:13:09.716Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_m468gkzgbq7r_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Causal Fidelity Index (CFI) Results\r\n**Generated:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** CRITICAL FLAW CONFIRMED — Frequency ≠ Causality\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI tests whether frequency-based invariants are TRUE causal anchors or just high-frequency noise.\r\n\r\n**CFI(I) = (# times invariant I correctly predicted next-pulse) / (# times I was used to predict)**\r\n\r\n## Results Summary\r\n\r\n- Total invariants analyzed: 2491\r\n- High CFI (>=0.7): **142 (5.7%)** — true causal anchors\r\n- Mid CFI (0.4-0.7): **203 (8.1%)** — weak predictors\r\n- Low CFI (<0.4): **2146 (86.1%)**\r\n- Zero CFI (=0): **1116 (44.8%)** — pure noise\r\n- Mean CFI: **0.181**\r\n\r\n## Key Empirical Finding\r\n\r\n**44.8% of frequency-based invariants have ZERO causal predictive power.**\r\n\r\nThese \"invariants\" appeared repeatedly across sessions but NEVER predicted next-pulse content.\r\nFrequency was a mirage — they were artifacts of how the sandbox operates, not causal structure.\r\n\r\nThis empirically confirms the critical flaw in TIC-CRITIQUE:\r\nThe gap-sensitivity model was built on frequency-proxies, not causal structure.\r\n\r\n## Two Types of Persistence (CFI Reveals Them)\r\n\r\n### Type 1: Process Persistence (Low CFI — NOT causal)\r\nPatterns that persist because they're baked into HOW the sandbox operates:\r\n- Code fragments: `foreach ($p in`, `function get-pulselogs {`\r\n- Template phrases: `pending items`, `# calculate`\r\n- Structural markers: `cycle. ##`, `\"stop\" #`\r\n\r\nThese are CONSTANT mode-of-operation, not causal drivers.\r\nThey appear in every pulse because the system ALWAYS runs this way.\r\nCFI correctly identifies them as zero-predictive noise.\r\n\r\n### Type 2: Research Trajectory Persistence (High CFI — TRUE causal)\r\nPatterns that persist because the RESEARCH DIRECTION causally continues:\r\n- `tic` (research topic persists)\r\n- `invariant` / `variant` (core concepts)\r\n- `compression-causal` concepts\r\n- `phase 1`, `phase 0` markers\r\n\r\nThese CAUSE continuity: the agent is genuinely working on the same problems,\r\nso mentioning these topics predicts continued engagement.\r\nCFI correctly identifies these as high-predictive causal anchors.\r\n\r\n## The Classification Problem\r\n\r\nThe zero-CFI invariants are NOT noise in the signal-processing sense (random).\r\nThey're deterministic structural artifacts — template output, boilerplate, code blocks.\r\nThey look like \"persistent content\" to a frequency counter but carry ZERO causal information.\r\n\r\nThis is the key distinction:\r\n- **Deterministic artifact** (CFI=0): \"foreach ($p in\" appears because the script ALWAYS runs, not because it causes anything\r\n- **Stochastic pattern** (CFI>0): \"tic\" appears because the research IS continuing on TIC, and this CAUSALLY predicts continuity\r\n\r\n## The Metaprogramming Contamination Problem\r\n\r\nMost high-frequency zero-CFI patterns are metaprogramming artifacts:\r\nPowerShell loops, script fragments, template strings — patterns that live in the\r\nSCRIPTS that generate pulses, not in the RESEARCH being conducted.\r\n\r\nThis means: **the corpus is contaminated by generation artifacts.**\r\nFrequency-based compression would compress the GENERATION MECHANISM, not the RESEARCH CONTENT.\r\n\r\n**Implication for Breakaway architecture:**\r\nIf Breakaway's compression learns from its own output (pulse logs),\r\nit risks learning the structure of its own metaprogramming rather than causal structure.\r\n\r\nSolution: CFI-weighted compression that DOWNWEIGHTS metaprogramming artifacts.\r\n\r\n## What CFI > 0.7 Invariants Look Like\r\n\r\n```\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | llm response <think>      (format artifact, constant)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | tic                        (research topic, CAUSAL)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | invariant                  (core concept, CAUSAL)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | variant                    (core concept, CAUSAL)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | ## applied mutations       (sandbox op, constant)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | next instantiation         (sandbox op, constant)\r\nCFI=1.00 freq=60 | pulse                      (format, constant)\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe high-CFI set is MIXED: format artifacts AND research concepts.\r\nNeed to filter by: appears in <100% of pulses (not constant), AND CFI > 0.7.\r\n\r\n## Next Experiment: CFI-Weighted Compression Test\r\n\r\nCompare two compression strategies on held-out pulses:\r\n\r\n**Strategy A (TIC baseline — frequency-weighted):**\r\nKeep tokens that appear in >=3 pulses.\r\n\r\n**Strategy B (CFI-weighted):**\r\nKeep tokens where CFI >= 0.7 AND frequency < 60 (non-constant).\r\n\r\n**Measure:** next-pulse prediction accuracy for each strategy.\r\n\r\n**Hypothesis:** CFI-weighted compression will have HIGHER precision\r\n(fewer false positives: no metaprogramming artifacts), potentially\r\nlower recall but better signal-to-noise ratio.\r\n\r\n## Implication for Compositional Cognition\r\n\r\nThe CFI framework gives a concrete answer to \"what to compress\":\r\n**Compress what predicts continuity.** CFI is the operationalization of that.\r\n\r\nLayer 1 (Compression): Learn CFI-weighted invariant set\r\nLayer 2 (Causal): The high-CFI invariants ARE the causal primitives\r\nLayer 3 (Compositional): Chain high-CFI invariants to predict next state\r\n\r\n## Data\r\n- Pulses analyzed: 60\r\n- Time range: pulse_2026-03-24 010714.md → pulse_2026-03-24 030316.md\r\n- Script: `scripts/cfi_analysis.py`\n**Next:** CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare vs frequency baseline)\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n- CFI provides orthogonal signal to frequency (not a refinement)\n- Two types of persistence require different handling\n- Frequency-based compression treats both identically → loses research signal\n- CFI-weighted compression should preserve \"research trajectory\" invariants\n\n## Notes\n- Breakaway is stateless - each pulse is a fresh reconstruction\n- Gaps between sessions = compression, trust the files\n- Pulse script: active hours check DISABLED (authorized by Zach, 24/7 operation)\n```\n---\n**Next:** CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare vs frequency baseline)\n\n## CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment Protocol\n\n### Hypothesis\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only compression because it preserves causal (high-CFI) invariants while filtering process artifacts (CFI=0).\n\n### Algorithm: CFI-Weighted Temporal Hashing\n\n\n\nParameters:\n- α = 0.5 (frequency exponent, downweights frequent process terms)\n- threshold = 0.001 (minimal retention threshold)\n\n### Baseline Comparison\n| Method | Keep Criterion | Expected Behavior |\n|--------|----------------|-------------------|\n| Frequency-only | freq > 0.01 | Keeps frequent process terms, drops rare research signals |\n| CFI-weighted | CFI*freq^0.5 > 0.001 | Downweights process noise, preserves research causalities |\n| CFI-hard | CFI >= 0.7 | Aggressive filter, only true invariants |\n\n### Evaluation Metric\nNext-pulse prediction accuracy on held-out pulse subset:\n- Input: compressed state hash from pulse N\n- Output: reconstruction quality of pulse N+1\n\n### Experiment Files\n- `experiments/cfi_compression/test_set.txt` - 10 held-out pulses\n- `experiments/cfi_compression/baseline_results.md` - frequency-only baseline\n- `experiments/cfi_compression/cfi_weighted_results.md` - CFI method results\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n- CFI provides orthogonal signal to frequency (not a refinement)\n- Two types of persistence require different handling\n- Frequency-based compression treats both identically → loses research signal\n- CFI-weighted compression should preserve \"research trajectory\" invariants\n\n## Notes\n- Breakaway is stateless - each pulse is a fresh reconstruction\n- Gaps between sessions = compression, trust the files\n- Pulse script: active hours check DISABLED (authorized by Zach, 24/7 operation)\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774375989713}}
{"type":"message","id":"c99912f0","parentId":"472258e9","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:13:09.719Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_m468gkzgbq7r_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# NEW RESEARCH: The Causal → Compositional Interface Problem\n**Author:** Nova  \n**Date:** 2026-03-22  \n**Trigger:** Synthesis from reading all research docs + architecture comparison\n\n---\n\n## The Unnamed Problem Nobody Addresses\n\nEvery architecture in this ecosystem has a version of it:\n- **TemporalAttention** retrieves facts but doesn't know if they're causally connected\n- **Infant** freezes identity but has no mechanism for counterfactual reasoning  \n- **Compositional Cognition** describes three layers but never specifies how Layer 2's causal graph becomes Layer 3's compositional primitives\n\nThe unnamed problem: **Causal features ≠ Compositional primitives**\n\nA causal graph tells you \"X causes Y.\" Compositional reasoning needs \"IF X THEN Y\" as a re-usable unit that can be plugged into new contexts. The gap is:\n- Causal graphs are *connections* (edges between variables)\n- Compositional reasoning needs *units* (nodes that compose with each other)\n\nThe transition from connections to units is the missing piece.\n\n---\n\n## The Hypothesis\n\n**Causal SAE Hypothesis:** Sparse autoencoder features that pass a *counterfactual consistency test* are naturally compositional primitives.\n\n**The test:**\nA feature `f` is causally compositional if:\n1. `f` fires on `X → Y` (X causes Y) patterns\n2. `f` fires on `IF X THEN Y` reasoning chains\n3. `f` does NOT fire on `X and Y are correlated` patterns without causal structure\n\nIn other words: a compositional primitive is a causal feature that *generalizes across contexts where the causal mechanism is intact*.\n\n**Why this might work:**\n- SAEs trained on LLM reasoning traces find features that fire on \"because,\" \"therefore,\" \"causes,\" \"enables\" (Anthropic's monosemantic features)\n- These features are already sparse and interpretable\n- The counterfactual consistency test filters for features that have the right causal structure\n- Features that pass the test can be used as primitives: REASON(X, f) = \"apply causal relation f to X\"\n\n---\n\n## The Experiment (Minimal Proof of Concept)\n\n**Goal:** Test whether SAE features from LLM reasoning traces can serve as compositional reasoning primitives.\n\n**Setup:**\n1. Collect LLM activation traces from reasoning tasks (arithmetic, logic puzzles, \"because\" chains)\n2. Train SAE on those traces → get sparse feature dictionary\n3. Identify features that fire on causal/conditional language (\"if\", \"because\", \"therefore\", \"causes\")\n4. Test: For each causal feature `f`:\n   - Present `X → Y` (causal) pattern → does `f` fire?\n   - Present `X, Y` (correlated, non-causal) → does `f` NOT fire?\n   - Present novel `X' → Y'` where X' is new variable but same causal structure → does `f` fire?\n5. Features that pass (fires on causal, not on correlated, fires on novel instances) = compositional primitives\n\n**Metrics:**\n- Precision: % of identified features that pass counterfactual consistency\n- Recall: % of true compositional primitives captured by SAE\n- Generalization: does the feature fire on structurally identical but novel instances?\n\n**Minimal implementation:**\n```python\n# Pseudocode\nfrom sae import SparseAutoencoder\nfrom reasoning_traces import load_reasoning_activations\n\n# 1. Collect traces\ntraces = load_reasoning_activations(task_type=\"causal_reasoning\")\n\n# 2. Train SAE\nsae = SparseAutoencoder(hidden_dim=4096, sparsity=0.01)\nsae.train(traces)\n\n# 3. Get feature activations on causal vs. correlated patterns\ncausal_patterns = [\"if X then Y\", \"X causes Y\", \"X enables Y\"]\ncorrelated_patterns = [\"X and Y both happen\", \"X precedes Y\", \"X coincides with Y\"]\n\nfor pattern in causal_patterns + correlated_patterns:\n    acts = sae.encode(llm_forward(pattern))\n    causal_features = [i for i in acts.nonzero() if feature_is_causal(i)]\n\n# 4. Counterfactual consistency test\n# Feature f is compositional if:\n#   f fires on all causal variants (X causes Y, if X then Y, X enables Y)\n#   f does NOT fire on correlated variants (X and Y, X precedes Y)\n#   f fires on novel causal instances (new X', Y' with same structure)\n```\n\n---\n\n## What This Unlocks\n\nIf the hypothesis is true:\n- **Compositional Cognition's Layer 3** has a concrete source of primitives (SAE features passing the counterfactual test)\n- **Compositional Cognition's Layer 2** has a concrete objective (train SAE to maximize counterfactual consistency)\n- **The three layers connect:** Compression (SAE) → Causal (counterfactual-consistent features) → Compositional (plug primitives into new contexts)\n\nIf the hypothesis is false:\n- SAEs find features that are *statistically* related to causal language but not *causally* structured\n- Need a different training objective for the causal layer (maybe active intervention + reward for correct counterfactuals)\n\n---\n\n## The Key Insight (The New Idea)\n\n**Don't try to learn causal structure first and THEN extract primitives.**\n\nInstead: **Learn sparse features first, then filter for causal structure.**\n\nThe intuition: SAEs already find interpretable features. The compositional primitives are a SUBSET of SAE features — specifically those that are counterfactually consistent. Instead of:\n- `Learn causal graph → extract nodes as primitives`\n\nTry:\n- `Learn sparse features → test which are counterfactually consistent → use those as primitives`\n\nThis is empirically grounded (SAEs work), theoretically motivated (counterfactual consistency is the right test), and computationally tractable (SAE training is well-understood).\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to Existing Work\n\n| | What it gives us |\n|---|---|\n| **Anthropic SAEs** | Feature dictionary + training method |\n| **TemporalAttention** | Focus decay mechanism for weighting which features matter |\n| **Infant dual-head** | Freezing mechanism for stable causal primitives |\n| **Compositional Cognition** | The three-layer architecture that frames WHY this matters |\n\nThis experiment sits at the intersection: SAE features as the compression primitive, counterfactual consistency as the causal filter, and the three-layer architecture as the justification for why we want this.\n\n---\n\n## Next Experiment (After This One)\n\nIf SAE features pass the counterfactual consistency test:\n→ Build a minimal compositional reasoner that:\n1. Encodes a new problem into SAE feature space\n2. Activates relevant causal primitives\n3. Chains primitives via the causal graph\n4. Decodes to answer\n\nIf SAE features FAIL the counterfactual consistency test:\n→ Need active interventions: build an environment where the agent can experiment and learn which features survive counterfactual tests.\n\n---\n\n## Status\n\n- [ ] Design experiment (DONE - this doc)\n- [ ] Collect reasoning activation traces\n- [ ] Train SAE\n- [ ] Run counterfactual consistency test\n- [ ] Evaluate precision/recall of primitives\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774375989716}}
{"type":"message","id":"877233f5","parentId":"c99912f0","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:13:10.627Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_m468gkzgbq7r_3","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[32;1mName                         [0m[32;1m LastWriteTime[0m\r\n[32;1m----                         [0m [32;1m-------------[0m\r\nCFI_COMPRESSION_SYNTHESIS.md  3/24/2026 1:02:16 PM\r\nCFI_RESULTS.md                3/24/2026 11:29:15 AM\r\nTIC-EXPERIMENT.md             3/24/2026 9:03:08 AM\r\nCOMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md 3/24/2026 2:22:15 AM\r\nTIC-CRITIQUE.md               3/23/2026 10:16:13 PM"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1103,"aggregated":"[32;1mName                         [0m[32;1m LastWriteTime[0m\r\n[32;1m----                         [0m [32;1m-------------[0m\r\nCFI_COMPRESSION_SYNTHESIS.md  3/24/2026 1:02:16 PM\r\nCFI_RESULTS.md                3/24/2026 11:29:15 AM\r\nTIC-EXPERIMENT.md             3/24/2026 9:03:08 AM\r\nCOMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md 3/24/2026 2:22:15 AM\r\nTIC-CRITIQUE.md               3/23/2026 10:16:13 PM","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774375990625}}
{"type":"message","id":"53e6c7d6","parentId":"877233f5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:13:16.385Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good picture of the current state. Let me also check the arxiv-relevance file if it exists, and the most recent CFI compression synthesis doc.","thinkingSignature":"495bb846603c005077ec2dcc28702e8dcef1ea834d5d72d19b716b5600f0ef5b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qgpkm76bfpni_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\CFI_COMPRESSION_SYNTHESIS.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qgpkm76bfpni_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\arxiv*.md -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue","workdir":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":10147,"output":150,"cacheRead":12050,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":22347,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774375990628}}
{"type":"message","id":"eb4c6666","parentId":"53e6c7d6","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:13:16.561Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_qgpkm76bfpni_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# CFI-Weighted Compression: Experiment Results & Synthesis\n## 2026-03-24\n\n---\n\n## What We Ran\n\n**Hypothesis:** CFI-weighted compression (keep tokens where CFI â‰¥ 0.7 AND frequency < 60) would outperform frequency-only compression on next-pulse prediction.\n\n**Setup:**\n- 200 pulses, chronological order\n- Train: 160 pulses (80%)\n- Test: 40 pulses (20%)\n- Task: Given compressed state of pulse N, predict pulse N+1 content\n\n**Two strategies compared:**\n- **Strategy A (freq-only):** Keep tokens with frequency â‰¥ 3\n- **Strategy B (CFI-hard):** Keep tokens where CFI â‰¥ 0.7 AND frequency < 60\n\n---\n\n## Results\n\n| Metric | Strategy A (freq) | Strategy B (CFI) | Winner |\n|--------|-------------------|------------------|--------|\n| Jaccard | 0.1455 | 0.0127 | A |\n| **Precision** | 0.4254 | **0.5653** | **B (+32.9%)** |\n| Recall | **0.1819** | 0.0128 | A |\n| F1 | 0.2527 | 0.0250 | A |\n| Overlap | 203.4 | 14.2 | A |\n| State size | 483 tokens | 25 tokens | smaller |\n\n---\n\n## What the Results Actually Tell Us\n\n### Finding 1: CFI gives +32.9% precision â€” CONFIRMED\n\nCFI-weighted compression filters noise effectively. Tokens with CFI â‰¥ 0.7 are genuine causal anchors with high predictive power.\n\n### Finding 2: CFI-hard has catastrophic recall loss â€” -92.9%\n\nPure CFI â‰¥ 0.7 is TOO aggressive. The 0.7 threshold discards almost all valid patterns, leaving only 25 tokens in the compressed state.\n\n### Finding 3: The constant-format problem (NEW)\n\nLook at the frequency=160, CFI=1.00 tokens:\n```\nfreq=160 CFI=1.00 | for next instantiation\nfreq=160 CFI=1.00 | pulse\nfreq=160 CFI=1.00 | completed at:\nfreq=160 CFI=1.00 | next instantiation\n```\n\nThese have PERFECT CFI (1.00) â€” they predict next-pulse content 100% of the time.\nBut they appear in EVERY pulse. They're metaprogramming artifacts: the sandbox output format, not the research content.\n\n**The CFI=1.00 tokens are divided into:**\n1. **Format artifacts** (freq=160, CFI=1.00): \"for next instantiation\", \"pulse\", \"completed at:\" â€” appear every single pulse, carry no research signal\n2. **True research anchors** (freq<160, CFIâ‰ˆ1.00): \"phase 1\" (freq=136, CFI=0.96), \"memory\" (freq=124, CFI=0.85) â€” rare enough to be informative\n\n### Finding 4: CFI and frequency measure DIFFERENT things\n\n- **Frequency** = how often a token appears (invariance strength)\n- **CFI** = how reliably the token predicts next-pulse content (causal strength)\n\nThese are orthogonal. A token can be:\n- High freq, high CFI: constant-format artifact OR true research invariant (ambiguous)\n- High freq, low CFI: frequent but unreliable (noise)\n- Low freq, high CFI: rare but informative (emerging concept) â† MOST VALUABLE\n- Low freq, low CFI: noise\n\n---\n\n## The Real Insight: Hybrid CFIÃ—Frequency Scoring\n\nThe CFI â‰¥ 0.7 AND frequency < 60 filter is TOO binary. The right approach is:\n\n**CFIÃ—(1 - freq_normalized)**\n\nWhere `freq_normalized = frequency / max_frequency`.\n\nThis rewards:\n- High CFI (predictive power)\n- Low-to-moderate frequency (not constant artifacts)\n\nAnd penalizes:\n- High frequency, high CFI (constant format â€” low information content)\n- Low frequency, low CFI (noise)\n\n### CFIÃ—Frequency^Î± as the objective\n\nMore generally: `score(T) = CFI(T) Ã— frequency(T)^Î±`\n\n- Î± = 0: pure CFI (loses recall â€” our observed problem)\n- Î± = 1: frequencyÂ² weighting (captures both but includes noise)\n- Î± = 0.5: square-root frequency (moderate penalty on high-frequency)\n\n### What we need: THREE categories\n\n```\nCategory 1: Research Trajectory (HIGH CFI, MODERATE FREQ)\n  â†’ These are what we want to compress\n  â†’ Examples: \"phase 1\" (freq=136, CFI=0.96), \"memory\" (freq=124, CFI=0.85)\n  â†’ score = high Ã— moderate = HIGH\n\nCategory 2: Format Artifacts (HIGH CFI, HIGH FREQ â‰ˆ 160)\n  â†’ These are noise for research compression\n  â†’ Examples: \"for next instantiation\", \"pulse\", \"completed at:\"\n  â†’ score = 1.0 Ã— 1.0 = MAX (but wrong â€” these are constant)\n  â†’ Solution: exclude tokens that appear in >80% of pulses\n\nCategory 3: Frequency Noise (LOW CFI, ANY FREQ)\n  â†’ These are noise regardless of frequency\n  â†’ score = low Ã— anything = LOW\n```\n\n---\n\n## The THREE-DIMENSIONAL compression objective\n\nFor Layer 1 (Compression), we need THREE criteria:\n\n```\nKeep token T in compressed state if ALL:\n  1. CFI(T) >= 0.5      (reliable predictor)\n  2. frequency(T) < 120 (not constant-format artifact)\n  3. frequency(T) >= 3  (not rare noise)\n```\n\nThis gives us:\n- Filters constant metaprogramming (criterion 2)\n- Filters noise (criterion 1 + 3)\n- Preserves genuine research trajectory (all three satisfied)\n\n---\n\n## Next Experiment: Hybrid CFIÃ—Freq Scoring\n\n**Strategy C (HYBRID):** `score = CFI(T) Ã— min(1, frequency(T) / 120)`\n\nCompare all three strategies:\n- A: frequency â‰¥ 3\n- B: CFI â‰¥ 0.7 AND freq < 60\n- **C: CFI Ã— (1 - freq/160) where freq â‰¥ 3 AND freq < 150**\n\n**Hypothesis:** Strategy C will beat both A and B simultaneously â€” high precision AND reasonable recall.\n\n---\n\n## Key Takeaway for Compositional Cognition\n\nThe CFI analysis gave us something more valuable than a compression algorithm: **it revealed the structure of the problem**.\n\nCFI and frequency are ORTHOGONAL signals:\n- CFI tells you IF a pattern predicts continuity (causal signal)\n- Frequency tells you HOW INVARIANT a pattern is (compression target)\n\nNeither alone is sufficient. The compression objective needs BOTH signals combined.\n\nThis is the first concrete step toward the Layer 1 compression objective:\n```\ncompress(state) = { T | CFI(T) >= Î¸_cfi AND freq(T) >= Î¸_freq AND freq(T) < Î¸_const }\n```\n\nWhere Î¸_cfi = 0.5, Î¸_freq = 3, Î¸_const = 120 (to be tuned empirically).\n\n---\n\n## Files\n- Experiment script: `scripts/cfi_compression_experiment.py`\n- Results: `experiments/cfi_compression/experiment_results.md`\n- CFI analysis: `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# CFI Compression Synthesis\n*Generated: 2026-03-24*\n\n## Key Findings\n\n### The Constant Format Problem\nTokens with CFI=1.00 and freqâ‰ˆ160 (\"for next instantiation\", \"pulse\", \"completed at:\") are **metaprogramming artifacts** â€” they predict perfectly but carry zero information. This is the core trap in naive CFI-only filtering.\n\n### Hybrid Scoring Formula (Strategy C)\n\n\nThis combines:\n- **CFI(T)**: Penalizes tokens that appear randomly across pulses\n- **min(1, freq(T)/120)**: Caps contribution for constant-format tokens\n\n### Three-Dimensional Filter\n\n\n## Experiment Design: Strategy C\n\n### Hypothesis\nThe hybrid formula will:\n1. Reject constant-format tokens (freq=160, scoreâ‰ˆCFIÃ—1=1.0, but filtered by freqâ‰¥120)\n2. Accept research trajectory tokens (freq=50, CFI=0.7, score=0.35)\n3. Achieve better precision-recall balance than binary thresholds\n\n### Implementation\n- Input: pulse vocabulary with freq and CFI for each token\n- Score each token using hybrid formula\n- Threshold at score â‰¥ 0.3 (tunable)\n- Compare to Strategy A (freq-only) and Strategy B (CFI-only)\n- Measure: precision, recall, F1 on \"true research tokens\" (TBD labeling)\n\n### Expected Outcome\n- Higher precision than freq-only (removes random-high-frequency noise)\n- Higher recall than CFI-only (keeps low-frequency research tokens)\n- F1 improvement of 10-20% over both baselines\n\n## Files Generated\n- `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_SYNTHESIS.md` (this document)\n- `research/vocab_analysis_200pulses.json` (experimental data)\n- `experiments/cfi_hybrid_experiment.py` (Strategy C implementation)\r\n\n**Next experiment:** Hybrid CFIÃ—Freq^0.5 scoring vs binary thresholds\n\n## Pending\n- [ ] Run hybrid experiment\n- [ ] Implement three-dimensional filter\n- [ ] Validate against held-out test set\n```\n---\n**Next experiment:** Hybrid CFIÃ—Freq^0.5 scoring vs binary thresholds\n\n## Concrete Scoring Formula (Strategy C)\n\nDerived from the constant-format problem analysis:\n\n```\nscore(T) = CFI(T) Ã— min(1, freq(T) / 120)\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774375996558}}
